I tend to view the Star Wars saga as more than just a story; but as a culmination of concepts and ideas (drawn heavily from Eastern mythological and philosophical thought processes). By this I mean the following:

1. The Force is a collective consciousness which permeates every living thing. It has no shape, form, smell or touch, but can be felt on metaphysical level. People who are able to harness the power of the Force have to undergo intensive training and attain the highest form of control over their minds.

2. The saga does not simply look at "Good vs. Evil" but also at the Good in Evil (Darth Vader) and the Evil in Good (Anakin Skywalker) - something which more accurately defines the grey nature of human character.

3. Darth Vader constantly talks about the completion of events that were destined to happen. This is a strong reference to the cyclical concept of time as understood in Indian philosophy.

When I look at all the 7 Episodes in the three different Trilogies that they have been released in, I surmise that Parts IV, V and VI were concept-based. Parts I, II and III were less concept-based and more story-based. However, since part III ultimately had to merge into Part IV, the Trilogy was sill anchored to the concepts. Part VII, however, disregarded the concepts portrayed by Lucas completely and focused on just a story to make it "sell".

For all the following reasons, I feel that Episode VII is simply a bastardization of not just the concepts built up in Parts IV, V and VI, but also a desecration of the story built up by all six prequels:

1. There is no respect for the Force. What took Anakin and Luke intensive training to master was achieved by Rey instantly at the exact time when she needed it most. Further, people in whom the Force is strong are recognized by their quick reflexes and ability to see a little into the future; not by their ability to instantly manipulate minds and move objects at will.

2. There is no respect for the Dark Side of the Force. Even though Kylo may have still been in training stage, he was apparently powerful enough to command forces of the First Order. However, he was portrayed as an incompetent rookie who slashed out idiotically with his saber at disappointing news and who was smirked at by the General. Disney has disparaged the Force and the Dark Side of the Force as mere magic tricks which get you out of a sticky situation or which can give an "interesting" twist to a plot which has already been milked dry.

3. Disney has just milked the "relation" card. Just because Luke turning out to be Vader's son was a huge commercial success, Disney had to make Kylo the son of Han and Leia. 

4. The characters are two-dimensional (at least in this Episode). Finn is a cliché example of a "trained killer who suddenly gets a conscience" and Kylo is just a rehash of Anakin Skywalker's story. I do not want to comment on Rey's character because her back-story is not revealed in its entirety in this part. 

In conclusion, I would never recommend a Star Wars fan to watch this movie.
